==={{Anchor|Structures}} Buildings and monuments===
[[File:Fire Dpt monument 100 RSD jeh.JPG|thumb|left|225px|Monument to the Heroes of the Fire Department, 100th Street]]
The eastern side of Riverside Drive, once a series of luxuriously finished rowhouses interspersed with free-standing nineteenth century [[mansion]]s set in large lawns, today is lined with luxury apartment buildings and some remaining town houses from 72nd to 118th Streets.

The brick-faced Schwab House occupies the site of "[[Riverside (house)|Riverside]]", built for steel magnate [[Charles M. Schwab]], formerly the grandest and most ambitious house ever built on the island of Manhattan. Among the more eye-catching apartment houses are the curved facades of [[The Colosseum (apartment building)|The Colosseum]] and [[The Paterno]] and the Cliff-Dwellers Apartments at 96th Street, with mountain lions and buffalo skulls on its friezes. The [[Henry Codman Potter]] house at 89th Street is one of the few remaining mansions on Riverside Drive; it houses [[Yeshiva Chofetz Chaim]]. [[Master Apartments|310 Riverside Drive]], a landmarked<ref>[http://www.neighborhoodpreservationcenter.org/db/bb_files/1989MasterBuilding.pdf NYC Landmarks Preservation Commission Report on the Master Apartments (1989)]</ref> 24-story [[art Deco]] skyscraper, is near [[Columbia University]] and the [[370 Riverside Drive]] building, which was erected in 1922&ndash;23 for approximately $800,000 by [[Schwartz and Gross|Simon Schwartz and Arthur Gross]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=67061 |title=370 Riverside Drive, New York City |publisher=SkyscraperPage.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-30}}</ref> Also, the [[Nicholas Roerich Museum]] is on 107th Street and Riverside Drive.

Among the monuments, sights, and institutions along its route are the Eleanor Roosevelt statue by Penelope Jencks,<ref>[http://www.blueofthesky.com/publicart/works/eleanorroosevelt.htm Eleanor Roosevelt Memorial]; [http://newyorkcitystatues.com/penelope-jencks/ Penelope Jencks]</ref> the [[Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument (New York)|Soldiers and Sailors Monument]], [[Anna Hyatt Huntington]]'s ''Joan of Arc'',<ref>[http://www.blueofthesky.com/publicart/works/joanofarc.htm Joan of Arc]</ref> the Fireman's Memorial at 100th Street (a focus of spontaneous dedications of flowers and [[teddy bears]] after the [[September 11 attacks]])<ref>[http://www.nycgovparks.org/sub_your_park/historical_signs/hs_historical_sign.php?id=12921 NYC Parks Dept.: Historical Signs: Fireman's Memorial]; [http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9503E3DC1E3FF932A15753C1A9679C8B63 ''New York Times'']</ref> [[Grant's Tomb]], The [[Interchurch Center]], [[Riverside Church]], [[Sakura Park]], [[Riverbank State Park]], [[Trinity Church Cemetery]], [[Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center]], and [[Fort Washington Park (New York)|Fort Washington Park]]. Across from the Henry Codman Potter house is the [[Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument (New York)|Soldiers and Sailors Monument]] (1902). At 99th Street is a memorial to Beaux-Arts architect [[John Merven Carr<U+00E8>re]] by his partner [[Thomas Hastings (architect)|Thomas Hastings]]. The Firefighters' Memorial at 100th Street was sculpted by [[Attilio Piccirilli]]. It was installed in 1913 and restored in the late 20th Century. 

