==Notable residents==

* [[Paul Krugman]] bought an apartment with his [[Nobel Prize in economics]] money.
* [[Grantland Rice]], American sportswriter
* [[Jim Rogers]], investor and financial commentator  
* [[Damon Runyon]], American newspaper man and author
* [[George Gershwin]] occupied a penthouse at 33 Riverside Drive.
* [[Sergei Rachmaninoff]] owned a townhouse at 33 Riverside Drive.
* [[Serge Sabarsky]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/26/arts/serge-sabarsky-83-art-dealer-and-expert-on-expressionism.html|title=Serge Sabarsky, 83, Art Dealer And Expert on Expressionism - New York Times|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=1996-02-26|accessdate=2013-09-07}}</ref> art dealer and art expert, lived at 110 Riverside Drive<ref>http://www.buchhandel.de/WebApi1/GetMmo.asp?MmoId=2515447&mmoType=PDF&isbn=9783791351643</ref>
* [[William Randolph Hearst]] owned a five story penthouse in the Clarendon at 137 Riverside Drive.  
* [[J. Robert Oppenheimer]] and his family lived at 155 Riverside Drive on 88th Street.<ref>Broad, William J., [http://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/30/science/30manh.html "Why They Called It the Manhattan Project"], New York Times, October 30, 2007. "Oppenheimer and his parents lived at 155 Riverside Drive, an elegant apartment building at West 88th Street. The superintendent, Joe Gugulski, said the family lived on the 11th floor, overlooking the Hudson River."</ref>
* [[Babe Ruth]], lived at 173 Riverside Drive, then moved to 110 Riverside Drive from 1942 until his death in 1948.
* [[Uwe Johnson]], German author, lived with his family from 1966 till 1968 at 243 Riverside Drive, today ''The Cliff Dwelling'' apartments
* [[Saul Bellow]], lived at 333 Riverside Drive in the 1950s.<ref>Literary New York: a history and guide, Susan Edmiston, Linda D. Cirino,  Houghton Mifflin, 1976 p. 268</ref>
* [[Ralph Ellison]], American writer, longtime resident of 730 Riverside Drive

